Exploration

Variable Analysis: Choice

Choice is a categorical variable. It tends to be a value that is either in Map1 or Map2 for that specific observation (except the times when the Map1 and Map2 values are missing), so it seems like players get to choose which option out of Map1 and Map2 they want to play on. There is also a MapVote variable showing the vote outcome, which backs my assumption.

The data set has 37 unique values, none of which are NAs. However, based on the cod_maps data set, we know there are supposed to be 28 unique maps. Therefore, we need to change the erroneous entries. The code used to view the number of unique values and fix them can viewed in Appendix A.

The most common choices were Crossroads Strike, Diesel and Standoff, being selected in 54, 49 and 47 games respectively. The least common choice was Miami, being picked 3 times. A visualization of the number of times each map was chosen can be seen below. A table with a view of the times each map is chosen can be viewed in Appendix A.

Variable Analysis: Eliminations

Eliminations is a quantitative variable that represents the number of kills a players gets in a given game. Depending on the game mode this can also effect the overall score of the game.

If we were to ignore observations where there is an NA in the Eliminations column, we can observe the average Eliminations:

Variable Analysis: TotalXP

TotalXP is a quantitative variable which determines how much progress a player makes in their ‘level’. Leveling up allows players to unlock new weapons, cosmetics, etc.

There are 31 observations where the TotalXP value is NA. After removing those instances, this is the summary:

##    min   max firstQuartile    mean thirdQuartile  median       sd
## 1 1935 45310       9878.25 15490.8       19921.5 14721.5 6972.383

The plot shows a broad range of total XP earned, with more players at lower levels than very high levels. The graph for TotalXP observations looks to be a right-skewed. The average TotalXP in a game can be seen at 15490.8. The skewness indicates that while the average game may have moderate experience, there are a number of highly experienced groups that may pull the mean up.

Answering Questions

What is the breakdown of the players’ match outcomes (win, lose or draw)?

The first step would be to split the Result value into two columns - one with the player’s team score and the player’s opponent’s score. The next step would be to create indicator variables to signify the outcome for the player (Won, Draw and Lost). Using these separated values, we can calculate the proportions and create a pie chart. The code written to manipulate the data for this task can be viewed in Appendix 1.

The ratio of games won, drawn and lost by the player is 0.5459057, 0.007444169 and 0.4466501 respectively.

These proportions can be visualized in a pie chart.

The player has won 54.6% of their games, and have lost 44.7% of their games. There are very few instances when they have drawn a game (0.7%).

What is the relationship between the TotalXP in a game and the number of Eliminations in a game?

This can easily be understood by visualizing the relationship between TotalXP and Eliminations. The game-type may have an effect on the relationship since they may apply different rules and gaols to the game, so we can create separate plots for each game type to provide us another perspective.

From the first plot, without taking game-type into consideration, we can see that there is a positive association between TotalXP and Number of Eliminations. The variance increases as the number of eliminations increases, which isn’t an issue as this is an inference question.

When looking closely at the collection of plots separated by game-type, we can come to the same conclusion: that as the number of eliminations increases in a particular game, so does the total XP earned The only exception is HC-Hardpoint, which has too few observations to comment on.

In conclusion, we can safely assume that the more eliminations a player makes, the higher their total XP would be.

Which maps are the most likely to win the map vote when they are an option?

The first step in answering this question is to do data cleaning. We must remove rows where the player joined the lobby after the vote, as well as rows where the map was chosen as a result of a tie. To remove rows where the player joined after the vote, we can simply remove rows where the MapVote variable value is blank. To remove the rows where the vote is tied, we can separate MapVote into two columns (‘Vote1’ and ‘Vote2’) and check if they are the same. If the votes are the same, we filter out those rows.

After that, it is important that the names of the maps are correctly spelled, without leading or trailing spaces. We can look at the distinct values for the Map1, Map2 and Choice columns in the cod_data data and pick out the typos. To ensure that the spelling is correct, we can refer to the cod_maps data which contains the names of all the maps. We can then replace the incorrect entries.

Once the cleaning is done, we should be ready to put the data in a format to do calculations. To find the percentage we will need to two sets of figures: the number of times each map is voted to be played and the number of times each map is an option.

To get the number of times each map is played, we can simply group by Choice and use summarize() to count the instances. We then convert this to a data frame. To find the number of times each map appeared as an option, we can apply a similar approach that we took to get the times each map was chosen. We group by Map1, summarize to count the number of times it appears, then arrange. The same is done for Map2. We then combine the data frames together and create a new column where we add the counts for Map1 and Map2 together.

Finally, we can combine the two resulting data frames together, before dividing the times each map was chosen by the frequency of the map being an option, and multiplying it by 100. We can arrange this in decreasing order to see the highest percentage maps first.

The code for the data wrangling and manipulation can be viewed in Appendix 2.

There have been games played in 28 unique maps. Crossroads Strike is picked 41 times, followed by Diesel with 38 and Express with 34. There are 6 maps where 30 or more games have been played, and there aren’t many games separating them. Miami and WMD are the least popular with 2 games, followed by Jungle with 3 games each.

Nuketown ’84 was the most popular map, with an 84.85% rate of being picked when it appeared as an option. Crossroads Strike, Raid, Diesel and Standoff were make up the rest of the top five, getting picked more than 71% of the time. A table with all the values can be viewed in Appendix 2.

The top 5 maps also appeared often as options, which implies to me that despite not appearing an equal amount of times as the other maps, this is a fair assessment of their popularity among Call of Duty players (though Nuketown ’84 appears a little less frequently than the others in the top 15, which may be to it’s advantage). A map like WMD or Jungle, however, only appear 10 and 12 times respectively. This low frequency may significantly effect their change of winning a vote for the worse; their percentage score may be higher if we had a greater sample size. Their scores are currently very low, and so it is not much of a concern to me.

Create a model using three different approaches, that predicts if a player wins a game based on the other variables in the data set. Choose a model that you think is best.

For the data wrangling portion, I created variables indicating if the player won (Win) or lost (Loss) the game (a ‘0’ in both fields implies a tie. I also narrowed down the variables in the data set to get rid of seemingly redundant variables (based on my understanding of their meanings and through intuition). For instance, I don’t think MapVote plays a legitimate part in predicting a win or loss, so I removed that. Date was a variable that I wanted to include, however it caused issues when testing the Linear Discriminant Analysis model, so I removed it. I also removed observations with NA values.

I performed a 80/20 training/validation split so that I could calculate the accuracy of the models at the end, to be able to compare their predictive qualities.

The three classification approaches that I chose were Random Forest, Linear Discriminant Analysis and Logistic Regression.

Random Forest is a machine learning approach that repeatedly selects bootstrap samples. A tree is then fit to each samples. The various predictions produced from these various models are combined in this classification task by majority vote. Bootstrapping is when a sample is taken of a data set using replacement, obtaining a sample with as many observations as the data set itself. As a result, some observations may not be used. A limitation of this is that the trees are usually highly correlated, resulting in highly correlated predictions.

Linear Discrimination Analysis is a dimensionality reduction technique that works by projecting data from multiple dimensions onto one dimension so it can be classified more easily. It identifies a linear combination of features that can classify the response. Linear Discrimination Analysis makes several assumptions about the data: that sample measurements are independent, distributions are normal, and co-variance is equal across classes. Any violations of these assumptions means a significant decrease in accuracy.

Last but not least, Logistic Regression. This machine learning technique models probability; in our case, of a binary outcome. With the resulting probabilities, we can compare it to a set threshold to see the ‘success’ and ‘failures’. I chose Win = 1 as the success, and Win = 0 as the failure. I decided on using 0.5 as a threshold, with which we can compare the predicted probabilities to.

Based on the accuracy scores for the three models, the model produced from the Linear Discriminant Analysis approach is best, with an accuracy rate of 0.5802469 It narrowly beats the Logistic Regression model, which has an accuracy of 0.5740741. The Random Forest approach scored 0.5246914. The calculations can be viewed in Appendix 3.

Since the Linear Discriminant Analysis approach is best, I would suggest using that model. This is created using:

bestModel <- lda(Win ~ ., data = Train)

A output with more details can be found in Appendix 3.

cod_data_split <- cod_data %>%
  filter(Result != '') %>%
  separate_wider_delim(cols = Result, delim = "-", names = c("PlayersTeam", "PlayersOpponents"))

Creating indicator variables and calculating the proportions for games won, drawn and lost.

cod_data_outcomes <- cod_data_split %>%
  mutate(across(PlayersTeam, as.numeric)) %>%
  mutate(across(PlayersOpponents, as.numeric)) %>%
  mutate(Won = ifelse(PlayersTeam > PlayersOpponents, 1, 0),
         Draw = ifelse(PlayersTeam == PlayersOpponents, 1, 0),
         Lost = ifelse(PlayersTeam < PlayersOpponents, 1, 0))

propWon <- sum(cod_data_outcomes$Won) /  nrow(cod_data_outcomes)
propDraw <- sum(cod_data_outcomes$Draw) /  nrow(cod_data_outcomes)

  summarize(Count = n()) %>%

  rename(Map = Map1)

percentage_map_chosen <- cbind(total_map_counts, choice_counts_summary) %>%

Appendix 3

Building the models and finding the accuracy scores:

#building the models:
#Random Forest
set.seed(123)
rfModel <- randomForest(as.factor(Win) ~ ., data = Train, ntree = 500, mtry = 3)

#Linear Discriminant Analysis
ldaModel <- lda(Win ~ ., data = Train)

#Logistic Regression
lrModel <- glm(Win ~ ., family = "binomial", data = Train)
set.seed(NULL)

#testing accuracy:
#Random Forest accuracy:
set.seed(123)
rfPredWin <- predict(rfModel, newdata = Validation, type = "response")
mean(rfPredWin == Validation$Win)
## [1] 0.5246914
set.seed(NULL)

#Linear Discriminant Analysis accuracy:
ldaPredWin <- predict(ldaModel, newdata = Validation, type = "response")
mean(ldaPredWin$class == Validation$Win)
## [1] 0.5802469
#Logistic Regression accuracy:
lrPredWin <- predict(lrModel, newdata = Validation, type = "response")
lrPredWin <- ifelse(lrPredWin > 0.5, 1, 0)
mean(lrPredWin == Validation$Win)
## [1] 0.5740741
